'''''Erkenntnis und wissenschaftliches Verhalten''''' ({{lang-en|Cognition and Scientific Behavior}}) is a 1936 book by the Norwegian philosopher [[Arne Næss]]. The work was influential and anticipated many themes familiar in subsequent [[analytic philosophy]].

==Publication history==
''Erkenntnis und wissenschaftliches Verhalten'' was published in 1936 by Norske Videnskaps-Akademi (the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]).{{sfn|Brunswik|1938|pages=105–107}}

==Reception==
===Academic journals===
''Erkenntnis und wissenschaftliches Verhalten'' received a positive review from the psychologist [[Egon Brunswik]] in ''[[Philosophy of Science (journal)|Philosophy of Science]]''. Brunswik wrote that psychology was gaining increased importance within philosophy and the sciences by becoming its "preferred center of organization", and that Næss's book was part of this trend. He believed that Næss presented a "new and modernistic" version of psychology that was more promising than the "psychologism" of the late 19th century, maintaining that Næss emphasized "objective psychology" over "subjectivistic" ideas. He credited Næss with an impressive "revolutionary keenness" in the way he questioned "the absolute character of the antagonism between the empirical and the logical, and, within the latter, between true and false." He concluded that Næss's book was an "interesting and promising first publication."{{sfn|Brunswik|1938|pages=105–107}}

The book was also reviewed in ''[[Theoria (philosophy journal)|Theoria. A Swedish Journal of Philosophy and Psychology]]'', and Næss replied to the review.{{sfn|Stadler|2010|page=23}}

===Evaluations in books===
The philosopher [[Alastair Hannay]], writing in ''[[The Oxford Companion to Philosophy]]'' (1995; second edition 2005), states that ''Erkenntnis und wissenschaftliches Verhalten'' is a seminal work, in which Næss anticipates many themes familiar in post-war analytic philosophy.{{sfn|Hannay|2005|page=663}} The historian and philosopher of science [[Friedrich Stadler]], writing in ''The Vienna Circle in the Nordic Countries'' (2010), commented that it was regrettable that ''Erkenntnis und wissenschaftliches Verhalten'' was not included in Næss's ''Selected Papers''.{{sfn|Stadler|2010|page=13}}

