'''I'm entitled to my opinion''' or '''I have a right to my opinion''' is a [[Formal fallacy|logical fallacy]] in which a person discredits any opposition by claiming that they are entitled to their opinion. The statement exemplifies a [[red herring]] or [[Cliché#Thought-terminating cliché|thought-terminating cliché]]. The logical fallacy is often presented as '''Let's agree to disagree'''. Whether one has a particular entitlement or right is irrelevant to whether one's assertion is true or false. To assert the existence of the right is a failure to assert any [[justification (epistemology)|justification]] for the opinion. Such an assertion, however, can also be an assertion of one's own freedom or of a refusal to participate in the system of logic at hand.<ref>{{cite book | chapter=The Right to Your Opinion | title=Crimes Against Logic | publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]] | last=Whyte | first=Jamie | year=2004 | location=New York | isbn=0-07-144643-5}}</ref><ref name="Deleuze D&R">{{cite book | title=Difference and Repetition | publisher=[[Columbia University Press]] | last=Deleuze | first=Gilles | chapter=The Image of Thought | year=1994 | location=New York | isbn=0-231-08159-6 | others=Paul Patton (trans.)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/law/columnists/article2047652.ece | title=Sorry, but you are not entitled to your opinion | publisher=[[News UK]] | work=[[The Times]] | date=August 9, 2004 | archiveurl=http://www.brickboard.com/OPINIONS/index.htm?id=1468712 | archivedate=February 8, 2011 | first=Jamie | last=Whyte | deadurl=no |subscription=yes}}</ref>

Philosopher [[Patrick Stokes (philosopher)|Patrick Stokes]] has described the expression as problematic because it is often used to defend factually indefensible positions or to "[imply] an equal right to be heard on a matter in which only one of the two parties has the relevant expertise".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stokes|first1=Patrick|title=You're not entitled to your opinion|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10839232|website=[[New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=7 April 2017|language=en-NZ|date=9 October 2012}}</ref>

