{{Japanese name|Nitta}}
{{Nihongo|'''Yoshihiro Nitta'''|にった　よしひろ|''Yoshihiro Nitta''|legal name 新田佳浩|born 21 January 1929}} is a Japanese university professor and philosopher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.u-tokyo.ac.jp/focus/en/people/k0001_01665.html|title=NITTA Yoshihiro {{!}} The University of Tokyo|website=The University of Tokyo|language=en|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref> He is reputed as one of the greatest people to have influenced the [[Japanese philosophy]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.lk/books?id=uuaTBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA340&lpg=PA340&dq=yoshihiro+nitta+professor&source=bl&ots=pXqwDxax8p&sig=WPYV3E6nR6BpEeHSEQnVI7w-5P8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjv9P6D8ZHdAhUEX30KHRPRDPIQ6AEwCHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=yoshihiro%20nitta%20professor&f=false|title=The New Yearbook for Phenomenology and Phenomenological Philosophy|last=Hopkins|first=Burt|last2=Crowell|first2=Steven|date=2015-03-24|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317401483|language=en}}</ref>

== Career ==
He studied from 1949 to 1957 at the [[Tohoku University]] in the field of philosophy. He also received a scholarship from the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation to study at the [[University of Cologne]].

Between 1970 to until his retirement in 1999, he taught philosophy as a full professor at the [[Toyo University]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.lk/books?id=EvrtCAAAQBAJ&pg=PR11&lpg=PR11&dq=yoshihiro+nitta+professor&source=bl&ots=y2Dgo7u2k3&sig=P8Gch_Hr0pKD0nJzc4hSJqpazCY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjv9P6D8ZHdAhUEX30KHRPRDPIQ6AEwBXoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=yoshihiro%20nitta%20professor&f=false|title=Japanese Phenomenology: Phenomenology as the Trans-cultural Philosophical Approach|last=Nitta|first=Y.|last2=Tatematsu|first2=H.|date=2012-12-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9789400998681|language=en}}</ref>

